2 5-62-128. Unlawful rooster fighting.
3 (a)(1) A person commits the offense of unlawful rooster fighting in
4 the first degree if he or she knowingly:
5 (A) Organizes, promotes, or profits from rooster fighting;
6 or
7 (B) Receives money for the admission of another person to
8 a location used for rooster fighting.
9 (2) Unlawful rooster fighting in the first degree is a Class D
10 felony.
11 (b)(1) A person commits the offense of unlawful rooster fighting in
12 the second degree if he or she knowingly:
13 (A) Pays to attend a rooster fight; or
14 (B) Participates in watching or carrying out an organized
15 rooster fight.
16 (2) Unlawful rooster fighting in the second degree is a Class A
17 misdemeanor.
18 (c) A person shall not be charged under this section solely for being
19 present near a rooster fight unless there is reasonable cause to believe that
20 the person paid to attend a rooster fight or was a knowing participant in
21 watching or carrying out an organized rooster fight.
22 (d) A rooster shall not be seized by law enforcement under this
23 section solely based on the arrest of a person for violating a provision of
24 this section unless there is clear and convincing evidence that the rooster
25 was used in rooster fighting.
26 (e) If a person is not convicted under this section, any seized
27 rooster shall be immediately returned to the owner.
28 (f) A seized rooster shall not be euthanized unless a licensed
29 veterinarian determines that the rooster is suffering from an untreatable
30 medical condition.
